<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-06-21T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-06-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="88" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d88">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00B/598: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-06-21T13:00:00+08:00">June 21, 1929—1
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 1:10 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>498. Your 195, June 14, 3 p.m., was repeated to the American Consul at
                            Harbin who has replied as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“June 18, 4 p.m. Recent arrivals and reports from Hailar and
                                    Manchuria Station indicate that conditions normal on the border
                                    and that no trouble even in Barga will occur this summer.
                                    Inclined to believe these false rumors by Soviet agents in order
                                    to intimidate Chinese.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>